BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wassaic-project-2027-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260701
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260702
SUMMARY:Deadline: Wassaic Project 2027 Residency Open Call
DESCRIPTION:The Wassaic Project runs a single 2027 Artist Residency open ca
 ll covering both the Winter Residency (January to April 2027) and the Summ
 er Residency (June to September 2027) in Wassaic\, New York. Residents rec
 eive a private studio (about 100 square feet in winter\, 200 to 300 square
  feet in summer)\, a private bedroom in a shared house with common spaces 
 and kitchen\, and access to a wood shop in both seasons and a print shop i
 n summer. Programming includes open studios\, group studio visits\, and in
 dividual artist talks. The residency operates on a sliding scale fee of US
 D 0 to 900 per session\, with the organization covering roughly USD 5\,000
  per person through donor and grant support. The open call is open to indi
 vidual artists\, collaborative teams\, groups of two or more\, and applica
 nts through the Family Residency program. This is the residency program\, 
 distinct from the separate Summer Exhibition open call.\n\nOrganisation: W
 assaic Project\nLocation: Wassaic\, New York\, USA\nAward: Studio space an
 d a private bedroom in a shared house provided\; the organization covers a
 pproximately USD 5\,000 per person through donor and grant support. Reside
 ncy fee on a sliding scale of USD 0 to 900 per session. USD 25 application
  fee (waivers available for financial hardship)\nDuration: Sessions range 
 from roughly 2 to 4 weeks within the Winter (Jan-April 2027) or Summer (Ju
 ne-Sept 2027) programs\n\nMore: https://www.wassaicproject.org/apply
URL:https://www.wassaicproject.org/apply
LOCATION:Wassaic\, New York\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:loghaven-artist-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260716
SUMMARY:Deadline: Loghaven Artist Residency
DESCRIPTION:Loghaven Artist Residency offers practicing artists time\, spac
 e\, and resources on ninety wooded acres in Knoxville\, Tennessee. Fellows
  stay in five rehabilitated historic log cabins with access to purpose-bui
 lt studio space. Each Fellow receives an USD 850 weekly living stipend\, a
  travel subsidy on a sliding scale from USD 400 to 800\, up to USD 200 in 
 materials shipping reimbursement\, and covered room and board. Residencies
  run from 2 to 6 weeks across sessions scheduled throughout 2027. The prog
 ram is open to artists at any career stage working in architecture\, dance
 \, interdisciplinary art\, music composition\, theater\, visual art\, and 
 writing\, including collaborative groups of up to nine people. Applicants 
 must be at least 21\, live more than 120 miles from Knoxville\, and be eli
 gible to work legally in the US\; international artists and degree-seeking
  students are not eligible.\n\nOrganisation: Loghaven Artist Residency\nLo
 cation: Knoxville\, Tennessee\, USA\nAward: USD 850 weekly living stipend\
 , travel subsidy USD 400 to 800\, up to USD 200 materials shipping reimbur
 sement\, plus room and board\, housing in historic log cabins\, and studio
  space USD 25 non-refundable application fee (fee waiver available on requ
 est)\nDuration: 2 to 6 weeks depending on session\n\nMore: https://loghave
 n.org/residencies/apply/
URL:https://loghaven.org/residencies/apply/
LOCATION:Knoxville\, Tennessee\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:studios-at-mass-moca-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261101
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261102
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Studios at MASS MoCA Residencies
DESCRIPTION:The Studios at MASS MoCA is a year-round residency program on t
 he museum's campus in North Adams\, Massachusetts\, hosting up to 10 artis
 ts at a time for stays of two or four weeks. It primarily welcomes visual 
 artists across all media and writers in all literary disciplines\, and app
 licants from around the world are encouraged to apply. Residents receive 2
 4-hour access to a private furnished studio\, lodging in nearby apartments
 \, and several communal meals each week\, plus museum membership benefits 
 and access to The Clark Art Institute. The program offers need-based finan
 cial aid (artists typically pay between USD 0 and USD 450 per week) and fu
 lly funded fellowships that cover all residency fees for up to four weeks.
  General application deadlines fall on May 1 and November 1 each year\, an
 d the application is free to submit.\n\nOrganisation: MASS MoCA (Massachus
 etts Museum of Contemporary Art)\nLocation: North Adams\, Massachusetts\, 
 USA\nAward: Provides private 24/7 studio space\, furnished housing\, and s
 even communal meals per week. Financial aid is available so artists reques
 ting it typically pay between USD 0 and USD 450 per week\, and fully funde
 d fellowships cover all residency fees for up to four weeks. Artists who f
 ully self-fund pay a subsidized rate of USD 650 per week.\nDuration: 2 or 
 4 weeks\n\nMore: https://massmoca.org/studios/
URL:https://massmoca.org/studios/
LOCATION:North Adams\, Massachusetts\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:rauschenberg-medical-emergency-grants-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261117
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261118
SUMMARY:Deadline: Rauschenberg Medical Emergency Grants
DESCRIPTION:The Rauschenberg Medical Emergency Grants\, administered by the
  New York Foundation for the Arts on behalf of the Robert Rauschenberg Fou
 ndation\, provide one-time grants of up to USD 5\,000 to help artists in f
 inancial need cover recent unexpected medical\, dental\, and mental health
  emergencies. The program is open to generative visual and media artists a
 nd choreographers working in visual arts\, film\, video\, electronic and d
 igital arts\, and choreography who live anywhere in the United States\, th
 e District of Columbia\, a Tribal Nation\, or a U.S. Territory. Applicants
  must be artists in financial need\, with adjusted gross income at or belo
 w USD 80\,000 for an individual or USD 160\,000 for joint filers\, and mus
 t not have received a Rauschenberg Medical or Dancer Emergency Grant in th
 e past five years. Eligible expenses include emergency medical bills\, dia
 gnostics\, consultations\, therapy\, prescription medications\, emergency 
 dental care\, and transportation to appointments. The grant does not cover
  lost wages\, general living expenses\, or care for anyone other than the 
 artist. Applications are accepted during defined cycles\, with the current
  cycle running roughly from late October to mid November.\n\nOrganisation:
  New York Foundation for the Arts (NYFA) / Robert Rauschenberg Foundation\
 nLocation: United States (remote application)\nAward: One-time grants up t
 o USD 5\,000\nDuration: One-time grant\n\nMore: https://www.nyfa.org/award
 s-grants/rauschenberg-medical-emergency-grants/
URL:https://www.nyfa.org/awards-grants/rauschenberg-medical-emergency-grant
 s/
LOCATION:United States (remote application)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:a-wrinkle-in-thyme-farm-fiber-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261231
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270101
SUMMARY:Deadline: Farm\, Flock and Fiber Artist in Residence
DESCRIPTION:A Wrinkle in Thyme Farm is a small\, women-owned diversified fa
 rm in Sumner\, Maine that offers a six-month live-in fiber arts residency 
 starting in May. The resident exchanges an average of 15 to 20 hours per w
 eek of farm work for a modest monthly stipend\, free private rustic housin
 g\, community meals\, farm-grown food\, and access to the fiber studio. Re
 sidents receive solo studio time plus one day a week of learning and colla
 boration with fiber artist Marty Elkin\, working with home-grown Maine woo
 l through felting\, dyeing\, knitting and spinning. The program also inclu
 des training in flock management\, animal husbandry and lamb care\, with t
 he option to add two months for lambing season. It is designed for emergin
 g fiber artists who are single females able to lift 50 pounds and work aro
 und a farm. Applications open in November with a December 31 deadline and 
 a non-refundable USD 25 application fee.\n\nOrganisation: A Wrinkle in Thy
 me Farm\nLocation: Sumner\, Maine\, USA\nAward: Modest monthly stipend (ar
 ound USD 400/month) in exchange for roughly 15 to 20 hours/week of farm wo
 rk\, plus free rustic private housing (solar power\, wood stove)\, shared 
 kitchen\, bath and WiFi\, community meals and farm-grown food\, dedicated 
 solo studio time\, and weekly collaboration with resident fiber artist Mar
 ty Elkin. USD 25 non-refundable application fee\nDuration: Six months begi
 nning in May\, with an optional two additional months for lambing and earl
 y lamb care\n\nMore: https://www.awrinkleinthymefarm.com/?page_id=1294
URL:https://www.awrinkleinthymefarm.com/?page_id=1294
LOCATION:Sumner\, Maine\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:kala-fellowship-program-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20270301
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270302
SUMMARY:Deadline: Kala Fellowship Program
DESCRIPTION:The Kala Fellowship Program supports international\, national\,
  and local artists producing innovative work in and across multiple media\
 , with an emphasis on Kala's specialized printmaking\, photography\, and d
 igital media equipment. The institute supports up to 6 artists per cycle w
 ith a USD 3\,000 stipend\, 24/7 access to its Berkeley facilities for 1 to
  9 months\, one month of housing for artists based outside the 9 Bay Area 
 counties\, a Kala class or workshop\, and a culminating group show in the 
 Kala Gallery. Applications are submitted through kala.slideroom.com and re
 quire a statement of interest\, an artist CV\, documentation of 5 to 10 re
 cent works\, and two references. Artists enrolled in a degree-granting pro
 gram during the fellowship period are not eligible. The application opens 
 in December with no fee through January 15\, after which a USD 25 applicat
 ion fee applies through the March 1 deadline.\n\nOrganisation: Kala Art In
 stitute\nLocation: Berkeley\, California\, USA\nAward: USD 3\,000 stipend\
 , 24/7 facility access for 1 to 9 months\, 1 month of housing for artists 
 outside the 9 Bay Area counties\, a Kala class or workshop\, and a group e
 xhibition USD 25 application fee (free if applying December through Januar
 y 15)\nDuration: 1 to 9 months within the July 2026 to June 2027 fellowshi
 p period\n\nMore: https://www.kala.org/residencies/fellowship-program/
URL:https://www.kala.org/residencies/fellowship-program/
LOCATION:Berkeley\, California\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:roswell-artist-in-residence-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20270315
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270316
SUMMARY:Deadline: Roswell Artist-in-Residence Program
DESCRIPTION:The Roswell Artist-in-Residence Program\, established in 1967 a
 nd run by The RAiR Foundation\, offers visual artists a year-long studio-b
 ased residency known as the Gift of Time. Each resident receives a private
  house and a studio on a fifty-acre complex\, with rent\, utilities\, repa
 irs\, and maintenance covered by the program. Artists also receive a month
 ly stipend of USD 1\,100 plus a USD 250 monthly materials stipend. The pro
 gram is open to professional visual artists aged 21 and older working in p
 ainting\, drawing\, sculpture\, printmaking\, photography\, video\, digita
 l media\, and installation. It does not support performance art\, writing\
 , music\, or production crafts. The application period for the next cycle 
 runs from January 1 to March 15\, 2027\, and international applicants are 
 accepted with visa support available.\n\nOrganisation: The RAiR Foundation
 \nLocation: Roswell\, New Mexico\, USA\nAward: USD 1\,100 per month stipen
 d\, plus USD 250 per month materials stipend from the Frederick Hammersley
  Foundation. Includes a private house and a studio with rent\, utilities\,
  repairs\, and maintenance covered. USD 26.32 application fee\nDuration: 1
 2 months (one year)\n\nMore: https://www.rair.org/application-info
URL:https://www.rair.org/application-info
LOCATION:Roswell\, New Mexico\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wassaic-project-2027-summer-exhibition-open-call@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260810
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260811
SUMMARY:Deadline: Wassaic Project 2027 Summer Exhibition Open Call
DESCRIPTION:The Wassaic Project is holding its annual Open Call for the 202
 7 Summer Exhibition\, for artists of all mediums\, including 2D work\, scu
 lpture\, video\, new media\, site-specific installation\, performance\, te
 xt\, poems\, essays\, and publication-specific work. Selected work is show
 cased alongside a diverse range of pieces and performances in and around h
 istoric Wassaic and Maxon Mills\; the 2027 Summer Exhibition will be free 
 and open to the public every weekend from 1 May to 12 September 2027. In a
 n effort toward W.A.G.E. certification\, all accepted artists receive a mo
 dest honorarium to participate. Artists interested in creating a site-spec
 ific installation are also eligible for an Exhibitions Fellowship to help 
 realize their work\; Fellows are offered a no-fee residency for 1-4 weeks 
 in April or May 2027 (artists interested in making site-specific work shou
 ld still apply regardless of whether they are interested in or able to be 
 in residence). The Wassaic Project cultivates and supports community for e
 merging and professional contemporary artists\, writers\, and other creati
 ves\, with a residency program housed in historic landmark buildings that 
 hosts 10 artists each month in the heart of a rural community. APPLICATION
 : requires application forms\, a CV\, and an artwork/portfolio\; submitted
  via SlideRoom. Application fee: USD 25 (no participation fee or additiona
 l fees). Deadline 10 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation: The Wassaic Project\nLo
 cation: Wassaic\, New York\, United States (in and around historic Wassaic
  and Maxon Mills).\nAward: A modest honorarium for all accepted artists (p
 art of the organization's effort toward W.A.G.E. certification). Artists c
 reating site-specific installations are also eligible for an Exhibitions F
 ellowship and a no-fee residency of 1-4 weeks in April or May 2027.\nDurat
 ion: The 2027 Summer Exhibition runs free and open to the public every wee
 kend\, 1 May to 12 September 2027. Optional fellowship residency of 1-4 we
 eks in April or May 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.wassaicproject.org/apply/su
 mmer-exhibition-faq
URL:https://www.wassaicproject.org/apply/summer-exhibition-faq
LOCATION:Wassaic\, New York\, United States (in and around historic Wassaic
  and Maxon Mills).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:atu-windgate-artist-in-residence-fall-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260703
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260704
SUMMARY:Deadline: Windgate Artist-in-Residence Fall 2026 (Arkansas Tech Uni
 versity)
DESCRIPTION:The Artist-in-Residence (AIR) program at Arkansas Tech Universi
 ty is an immersive experience within an art and educational community\, in
 tended to advance the careers of practicing artists\, present residents as
  role models for the ATU community\, and strengthen public awareness of th
 e significance of making art and its effect on the surrounding community. 
 The residency takes place over a five-month period\, giving the artist tim
 e and space to focus on the creative process. For Fall 2026\, the program 
 will select an artist to create a public artwork that enhances the ATU cam
 pus\; both two-dimensional and three-dimensional proposals will be conside
 red. The program is supported by a generous grant from the Windgate Charit
 able Foundation. The Department of Art at ATU offers programs in Fine Art\
 , Graphic Design\, Game and Interactive Media Design\, and Art Education\,
  with a facility in Norman Hall featuring a professional gallery\, compute
 r lab\, lecture hall\, and studios for painting\, drawing\, printmaking\, 
 sculpture\, ceramics\, and graphic design. RESIDENCY DETAILS & EXPECTATION
 S: residents must be artists with significant exhibition records\, strong 
 communication skills\, sustained studio practice\, and a desire to engage 
 with the larger campus community\; involvement may include guest lecturing
 \, public talks\, mentoring students\, open studios\, and/or collaborating
  with faculty and students. The resident sometimes teaches one course in 2
 D Design\, 3D Design\, or Introduction to Drawing during their stay when e
 nrollment allows. Artists are expected to commit as a full-time resident f
 or the Fall academic term 2026. BENEFITS: USD 30\,000 stipend (minus fring
 es)\, USD 18\,000 for supplies\, a 2-bed/2-bath campus apartment\, and a l
 arge climate-controlled off-campus studio. Deadline 3 July 2026.\n\nOrgani
 sation: Arkansas Tech University (supported by the Windgate Charitable Fou
 ndation)\nLocation: Russellville\, Arkansas\, United States (Russellville 
 campus\, in the Arkansas River Valley\, about one hour from Little Rock). 
 In-person\, full-time residency.\nAward: USD 30\,000 stipend (minus fringe
 s) plus USD 18\,000 for supplies. Housing provided (a 2-bed\, 2-bath campu
 s apartment) and a large\, climate-controlled\, dedicated off-campus studi
 o space.\nDuration: Five-month residency over the Fall academic term 2026.
 \n\nMore: https://www.atu.edu/academicaffairs/faculty/adjunct/docs/AIR%20A
 D%20FALL%202026.pdf
URL:https://www.atu.edu/academicaffairs/faculty/adjunct/docs/AIR%20AD%20FAL
 L%202026.pdf
LOCATION:Russellville\, Arkansas\, United States (Russellville campus\, in 
 the Arkansas River Valley\, about one hour from Little Rock). In-person\, 
 full-time residency.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:creative-philadelphia-msb-interpretive-panels-2026@artificialnouveau.gi
 thub.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260712
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260713
SUMMARY:Deadline: MSB Interpretive Panels: Public Art Commission (Creative 
 Philadelphia)
DESCRIPTION:Creative Philadelphia announces a call to commission a series o
 f permanent interpretive panels with integrated augmented reality (AR) com
 ponents at the Municipal Services Building in Center City Philadelphia. Th
 e commission is part of a broader initiative that includes an upcoming pub
 lic sculpture of Dr. Sadie T.M. Alexander by artist Vinnie Bagwell. Inspir
 ed by Alexander's groundbreaking legacy in public service\, these interpre
 tive panels will celebrate the City of Philadelphia's municipal employees 
 (past\, present\, and future) and provide deeper context for understanding
  Dr. Alexander's impact\; they will be located in front of the building's 
 landscaped areas\, flanking the upcoming sculpture\, and are intended to c
 omplement and support the overall site experience. SCOPE: an artist team w
 ill design and fabricate four (4) permanent\, sculptural interpretive pane
 ls incorporating augmented reality (AR) elements to expand storytelling be
 yond the physical surface of the artwork. ELIGIBILITY: all interested arti
 sts are invited to apply\; Philadelphia-based artists are strongly encoura
 ged\, though artists from outside the region will be considered\; multiple
  in-person site visits are required and associated travel costs must be co
 vered within the project budget. SELECTION: a two-part process: Part 1 sub
 mission of qualifications\; Part 2 finalist proposals and interviews. Up t
 o three (3) finalists are invited to submit short concept proposals and at
 tend an interview\; at no point should artists submit design proposals. BU
 DGET: USD 250\,000 total (see amount for the required cost breakdown). An 
 Artist Informational Meeting is held via Zoom on 30 June\, 6:00-7:00pm. Ap
 plication questions: paige.phillips@phila.gov. Apply via Submittable. Dead
 line 12 July 2026 (submissions close Monday 13 July 2026\, 6:00 AM).\n\nOr
 ganisation: Creative Philadelphia (Office of Arts\, Culture and the Creati
 ve Economy)\nLocation: Municipal Services Building\, Center City\, Philade
 lphia\, Pennsylvania\, United States. Philadelphia-based artists strongly 
 encouraged\; artists from outside the region considered. Multiple in-perso
 n site visits required (travel costs covered within the project budget).\n
 Award: Total project budget of USD 250\,000\, which must cover: artist fee
 s (18% design fee)\, design and engineering\, fabrication and installation
 \, structural footings/anchoring\, travel and site visits\, AR development
  (software\, hosting\, content production)\, insurance (1%)\, community en
 gagement participation\, and a service warranty keeping content compatible
  with new mobile OS versions for a minimum of 10 years. No application fee
 s.\nDuration: Permanent public artwork commission\; two-part selection pro
 cess.\n\nMore: https://oacce.submittable.com/submit/357418/msb-interpretiv
 e-panels
URL:https://oacce.submittable.com/submit/357418/msb-interpretive-panels
LOCATION:Municipal Services Building\, Center City\, Philadelphia\, Pennsyl
 vania\, United States. Philadelphia-based artists strongly encouraged\; ar
 tists from outside the region considered. Multiple in-person site visits r
 equired (travel costs covered within the project budget).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:neiu-art-design-studio-art-residency-2026-2027@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260809
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260810
SUMMARY:Deadline: NEIU Art + Design Studio Art Residency 2026-2027
DESCRIPTION:The NEIU Art + Design Studio Art Residency strives to create vi
 sible connections between Northeastern Illinois University's diverse popul
 ation of art and design students and working artists who embody these iden
 tities\, providing insights and inspiration through a dynamic exchange of 
 ideas and techniques. Visiting Artists should demonstrate a commitment to 
 their artistic practice and an interest in engaging with NEIU's students a
 nd creative community. Each Visiting Artist is awarded an honorarium and h
 as full access for a semester to the NEIU Art + Design facilities specific
  to their project\; over the residency they showcase their work in a publi
 c academic forum\, lead a hands-on workshop\, and participate in a Portfol
 io Review Day for NEIU's Art + Design students. FACILITIES (in the Salme H
 arju Steinberg Fine Arts Center) include a Design Studio with the largest 
 collection of Riso drums at any Chicago university\, a Fab Lab (FDM and re
 sin 3D printers\, large-format CNC router\, vinyl cutters\, laser cutters)
 \, a Ceramic Studio (throwing wheels\, glaze room\, electric and gas kilns
 \, raku area)\, a Letterpress Studio (two Vandercook presses\, metal and w
 ood type)\, a Sculpture Studio (wood shop\, clay modeling and spray painti
 ng areas)\, a Photography Studio (analog and digital\, plus a lighting stu
 dio)\, and fully equipped Painting\, Drawing\, and Printmaking studios. BE
 NEFITS: USD 800 honorarium\; facility access based on project focus (Art +
  Tech\, Ceramics\, Drawing\, Painting\, Photography\, Printmaking\, Sculpt
 ure)\, with supplies requestable subject to approval\; and the opportunity
  to exhibit in a group exhibition in the NEIU Fine Arts Center Gallery. PA
 RTICIPATION: lead a 2-hour hands-on workshop for 15-20 students on a topic
  relevant to the project\; give an hour-long artist talk with Q&A\; and se
 rve as a guest panelist for a day-long portfolio review. KEY DATES: open c
 all 2 June - 9 August\; emailed acceptances in October\; Residency Session
  1 runs 25 January - 14 May and Session 2 runs 30 August - 11 December. Ap
 ply via the JotForm application. Deadline 9 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation: 
 Northeastern Illinois University (NEIU)\, Art + Design Department\nLocatio
 n: Salme Harju Steinberg Fine Arts Center\, Northeastern Illinois Universi
 ty\, Chicago\, Illinois\, United States. In-person\; semester-long access 
 to NEIU facilities.\nAward: USD 800 honorarium\, plus a semester of full a
 ccess to NEIU Art + Design facilities specific to the project (Art + Tech\
 , Ceramics\, Drawing\, Painting\, Photography\, Printmaking\, Sculpture)\;
  supplies can be requested with guidance and approval from Studio Area per
 sonnel. Visiting Artists may also exhibit in a group exhibition in the NEI
 U Fine Arts Center Gallery.\nDuration: One semester. Residency Session 1: 
 25 January - 14 May\; Session 2: 30 August - 11 December.\n\nMore: https:/
 /form.jotform.com/261044627286156
URL:https://form.jotform.com/261044627286156
LOCATION:Salme Harju Steinberg Fine Arts Center\, Northeastern Illinois Uni
 versity\, Chicago\, Illinois\, United States. In-person\; semester-long ac
 cess to NEIU facilities.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:art-shanty-projects-performances-art-actions-2027@artificialnouveau.git
 hub.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260709
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260710
SUMMARY:Deadline: Art Shanty Projects 2027: Call for Performances + Art Act
 ions
DESCRIPTION:Art Shanty Projects seeks winter enthusiasts and creative adven
 turers to create performances and art actions for its 2027 Program on Bde 
 Uman (Lake Harriet) in Minneapolis. It invites music-makers\, poets\, buil
 ders\, scientists\, dancers\, puppeteers\, writers\, dreamers\, activists\
 , outdoors-people\, conversationalists\, craftspeople\, storytellers\, and
  more to propose new and innovative ways to engage artistically with the p
 ublic in the social context of a village on a frozen lake (or winter 'beac
 h'\, as climate change may necessitate). ASP has an expansive notion of wh
 at constitutes a performance or art action\, having welcomed dance\, creat
 ive sporting events\, happenings\, carnival games\, music\, roving dance\,
  temporary sculpture\, puppet shows\, artful haircuts\, advice booths\, cl
 imate actions\, and more. NOTE: this call is for PERFORMANCES + ART ACTION
 S only (a separate call exists for shanty artists). Since 2004\, Art Shant
 y Projects has created joyful winter art experiences inspired by pop-up ic
 e fishing villages\, using the frozen lake as a public platform for a temp
 orary creative community with tens of thousands of annual visitors. ASP is
  deeply committed to social\, racial\, gender\, and economic justice and t
 o accessibility (embracing the spirit of the ADA). ELIGIBILITY: everyone i
 s eligible (artists at all career stages)\; applicants need not have exper
 ience with everything asked\, but should show eagerness to engage\, develo
 p new skills\, and stay open to new perspectives. Projects that involve se
 lling anything or the exchange of legal currency will not be accepted. COM
 PENSATION: sliding-scale stipend up to USD 1\,000 plus extensive productio
 n and logistical support. PROGRAM: on-ice every Saturday and Sunday\, 10am
 -4pm\, 16 January to 7 February 2027\; selected artists notified mid-Augus
 t 2026\, with mandatory in-person meetings (at least one team member) star
 ting 10 September 2026. Apply via the Google form (preferred) or the no-Go
 ogle-account alternative. Contact Erin Lavelle\, Artistic Director: progra
 m@artshantyprojects.org. Deadline for proposal submissions: 9 July 2026\, 
 11:59pm CST.\n\nOrganisation: Art Shanty Projects\nLocation: Bde Uman (Lak
 e Harriet)\, Minneapolis\, Minnesota\, United States. On-ice program plus 
 several mandatory in-person meetings in Minneapolis\; in-person participat
 ion required.\nAward: Sliding-scale stipend up to USD 1\,000 (request an a
 mount that fits the project: roughly USD 1\,000 for full-day/most-ambitiou
 s activities\, USD 500 for half-day\, USD 250 for short or one-off/solo/lo
 w-production activities). Plus direct production support\, discounted mate
 rials and resource sharing\, a shared warming shanty\, a hot meal\, snacks
 \, hot beverages\, hand/toe warmers\, one parking space per project\, on-s
 ite medic\, and ASL interpreter/audio describer for the public. No applica
 tion fees.\nDuration: On-ice program every Saturday and Sunday\, 10am-4pm\
 , 16 January to 7 February 2027\, with production meetings and mandatory c
 heck-ins from September 2026 onward.\n\nMore: https://artshantyprojects.or
 g/2027-call-for-performances-art-actions/
URL:https://artshantyprojects.org/2027-call-for-performances-art-actions/
LOCATION:Bde Uman (Lake Harriet)\, Minneapolis\, Minnesota\, United States.
  On-ice program plus several mandatory in-person meetings in Minneapolis\;
  in-person participation required.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mak-center-artists-architects-residence-2027-2028@artificialnouveau.git
 hub.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260812
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260813
SUMMARY:Deadline: MAK Center: Artists and Architects in Residence 2027/2028
  (MAK Schindler Scholarship\, Los Angeles)
DESCRIPTION:The MAK Center for Art and Architecture awards Artists and Arch
 itects in Residence scholarships (the MAK Schindler Scholarship) to indepe
 ndent projects exploring the relation between art and architecture. Projec
 ts are chosen for their ability to critically examine current trends in ar
 t\, architecture and society\; to make a compelling connection with Los An
 geles as the place of implementing or continuing the applicant's own work\
 ; and to demonstrate a conceptual and experimental approach. Emphasis is p
 laced on the L.A. location\, and residents' projects often reflect\, incor
 porate and address specific facets of the city and its social fabric. Reci
 pients are encouraged to take part in the MAK Center's activities and to a
 ttend meetings\, workshops and project discussions with other artists and 
 students. ELIGIBILITY: freelance artists\; fine arts or architecture stude
 nts at a university who have completed the '2. Studienabschnitt'\; or arch
 itects or artists who have recently graduated. Teams of up to three are el
 igible if all members practice together as an artist group or collective o
 f architects\, are all present in L.A. for the six months\, and name a con
 tact responsible for the team. HOUSING: the Mackey Apartments are made ava
 ilable to scholarship holders only\; family members\, relatives and friend
 s may be accommodated for a maximum of two weeks during the term\, permitt
 ed in advance by Beth Stryker\, Director of the MAK Center. Eligibility is
  excluded if the applicant has been or will be granted another scholarship
  in the USA immediately before or after the MAK scholarship\, or if the da
 ta form is incomplete or the required portfolio is missing. Residency term
 s run October to March and April to September. Deadline 12 August 2026. Ap
 ply: https://www.makcenter.org/apply-mackey\n\nOrganisation: MAK Center fo
 r Art and Architecture\, Los Angeles\nLocation: Los Angeles\, California\,
  United States (Mackey Apartments). Residents must be present in L.A. for 
 the full six-month term.\nAward: Six-month MAK Schindler Scholarship resid
 ency with accommodation provided at the Mackey Apartments. The open call d
 oes not state a stipend\, travel or honorarium figure\; confirm any additi
 onal financial support directly with the MAK Center. No application fee st
 ated.\nDuration: Six months. Residency terms run October to March or April
  to September\; 2027/2028 cycle.\n\nMore: https://www.makcenter.org/apply-
 mackey
URL:https://www.makcenter.org/apply-mackey
LOCATION:Los Angeles\, California\, United States (Mackey Apartments). Resi
 dents must be present in L.A. for the full six-month term.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:springboard-rural-regenerator-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.
 io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260618
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260619
SUMMARY:Deadline: Springboard for the Arts: Rural Regenerator Fellowship 20
 26
DESCRIPTION:The Rural Regenerator Fellowship is an 18-month fellowship that
  brings together rural artists\, creatives\, and culture bearers to deepen
  their relationships\, grow their work\, and support rural exchange and so
 lidarity across the Upper Midwest. Since 2021\, Springboard for the Arts h
 as invested more than USD 1 million in rural cultural organizers across th
 e Upper Midwest\, building a lasting network of support\, solidarity\, and
  exchange\; 44 Fellows have come together to support each other's work and
  share ideas. The fellowship brings rural artists into a supportive peer n
 etwork\, helping to sustain and deepen their existing work while cultivati
 ng geographic exchange\, mutual support\, and solidarity across the rural 
 Midwest. CURRENT CYCLE - Organizing for Care\, Safety\, and Solidarity: th
 is cycle supports artists who are organizing their rural places for care\,
  safety\, and solidarity. Six rural artists\, creatives\, and culture bear
 ers will each receive an unrestricted award of USD 15\,000\, one in-person
  retreat\, USD 3\,000 to support travel for Fellow Exchanges\, and the opp
 ortunity to attend and present at Springboard's Rural Futures Summit. Peer
 s\, collaborators\, and supporters may nominate a rural artist\, though no
 mination is not required to apply and all applications are reviewed equall
 y (the selection committee does not know whether an applicant was nominate
 d). Deadline to apply: 18 June 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Springboard for the 
 Arts\nLocation: Upper Midwest\, USA (rural communities). In-person retreat
  and Rural Futures Summit\nAward: USD 15\,000 unrestricted award per Fello
 w\, plus one in-person retreat\, USD 3\,000 to support travel for Fellow E
 xchanges\, and the opportunity to attend and present at Springboard's Rura
 l Futures Summit. Six Fellows selected. No application fee mentioned.\nDur
 ation: 18-month fellowship\n\nMore: https://springboardforthearts.org/prog
 rams/rural-regenerator/
URL:https://springboardforthearts.org/programs/rural-regenerator/
LOCATION:Upper Midwest\, USA (rural communities). In-person retreat and Rur
 al Futures Summit
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:lighthouse-works-fellowship-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261015
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261016
SUMMARY:Deadline: Lighthouse Works: Fellowship Program 2027 (Fishers Island
 )
DESCRIPTION:Lighthouse Works' Fellowship Program supports a diverse range o
 f cultural producers working at the vanguard of their creative fields. Fel
 lowships are six weeks in length\, occur year-round\, and provide fellows 
 with housing\, food\, studio space\, and USD 1\,750 in financial support. 
 Fellows enjoy a private bedroom and share a kitchen\, bathrooms\, and livi
 ng space in a 3-story Victorian house\; all dietary needs are accommodated
 \, and on most nights Lighthouse Works staff cook for and eat dinner with 
 the fellows. Studios are located about 1.5 miles (a 30-minute walk) from t
 he fellowship house\, are private and flooded with light\, and face the oc
 ean adjacent to Silver Eel Cove where the island ferry arrives. Lighthouse
  Works also maintains a wood and metal fabrication shop and a kiln. While 
 in residence\, a fellow's primary obligation is to pursue their own work\,
  though every fellow participates in two events\, an Artist Talk and Open 
 Studio\, that bookend the fellowship\; the program's intimate size allows 
 for conversation\, critique\, and collaboration. Artistic excellence is th
 e primary criterion for acceptance. Artists at any stage of their career a
 re encouraged to apply through the online Slideroom system. SELECTION: sta
 ff review applications for completeness\, a jury of experts in each artist
 's field reviews complete applications and identifies finalists\, intervie
 ws are scheduled in early January\, and applicants are notified in mid-Jan
 uary. The program is supported in part by a grant from the Robert Rauschen
 berg Foundation. APPLICATION CALL: Lighthouse Works accepts applications e
 ach year from September to October (the 2026 portal was open 15 September 
 to 15 October 2025). The deadline shown here is the anticipated close of t
 he next annual call for the 2027 cycle\; confirm exact dates on the Lighth
 ouse Works site when the portal reopens. Apply at http://thelighthousework
 s.slideroom.com.\n\nOrganisation: Lighthouse Works\nLocation: Fishers Isla
 nd\, New York\, USA (in-person residency)\nAward: Six-week fellowship prov
 iding housing\, food\, private studio space\, and USD 1\,750 in financial 
 support. No application fee mentioned.\nDuration: 6 weeks\; fellowships oc
 cur year-round across five sessions\n\nMore: https://lighthouseworks.us/fe
 llowship
URL:https://lighthouseworks.us/fellowship
LOCATION:Fishers Island\, New York\, USA (in-person residency)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:cali-futures-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260828
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260829
SUMMARY:Deadline: CALI Futures 2026
DESCRIPTION:CALI Futures supports artists and cultural workers across Calif
 ornia\, individually and in teams\, who are meaningfully contributing to a
 lternative efforts outside of conventional nonprofit and for-profit arts a
 nd culture systems. The Fund encourages work focused on income\, ownership
 \, and care\, and uplifts the role of artists and cultural workers in shap
 ing and sustaining alternative efforts that provide greater financial stab
 ility\, strengthen creative ownership\, and deepen mutual support across t
 he broader arts ecosystem. Project-restricted grants of USD 5\,000 are awa
 rded through a competitive process. Competitive applicants present (a) a c
 lear project request\; (b) proof of an active\, current artistic or cultur
 al practice\; (c) a description of their contribution to an alternative ef
 fort that improves financial sustainability\, creative ownership\, or mutu
 al support and addresses challenges not sufficiently solved by conventiona
 l nonprofit or for-profit sectors\; and (d) framing that ambitiously descr
 ibes the larger implications of this work for transforming artists' lives 
 and future cultural possibilities. The Fund supports individuals and teams
  at every stage\, from initial ideas to research\, implementation\, experi
 mentation\, and reflection. ELIGIBILITY: applicants must be individual art
 ists or cultural workers (cultural producers\, culture bearers\, creatives
 \, cultural practitioners)\; must reside full-time in California\; must be
  contributing to an alternative effort improving financial sustainability\
 , creative ownership\, or mutualistic social support within the arts and c
 ulture sector\; and that contribution must have occurred or begun on or af
 ter 1 January 2020. Teams are eligible\, but all team members must meet th
 e criteria and only one application is accepted per team (one member appli
 es and is responsible for grant requirements). INELIGIBLE: individuals wit
 hout an active practice\; organizations seeking operating or program suppo
 rt\; arts administrators\; individuals living or working outside Californi
 a\; past CALI Catalyst grantees describing the same project funded in 2021
 -2025\; incomplete applications\; and those with a conflict of interest wi
 th CCI or Hewlett Foundation board\, staff\, or directors. The Fund is adm
 inistered by the Center for Cultural Innovation (CCI) with funding from th
 e William and Flora Hewlett Foundation. TIMELINE: applications open 9 June
  2026 at 9:00 a.m. PT\; deadline 28 August 2026 at 11:59 a.m. PT\; review 
 September to November 2026\; notifications by 17 November 2026. Submitted 
 via Submittable. Questions: grants@cciarts.org (include CALI FUTURES in th
 e subject line) or 415.288.0530.\n\nOrganisation: Center for Cultural Inno
 vation (CCI)\nLocation: California\, USA. Applicants must reside full-time
  in California\nAward: USD 5\,000 project-restricted grants\, awarded comp
 etitively. USD 100\,000 total available each year across the 2026-2028 fun
 ding cycle. No application fee.\nDuration: Grant support period December 2
 026 to December 2027\n\nMore: https://www.cciarts.org/cgi/page.cgi/cali_fu
 tures.htm
URL:https://www.cciarts.org/cgi/page.cgi/cali_futures.htm
LOCATION:California\, USA. Applicants must reside full-time in California
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:van-alen-open-access-exhibition-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260628
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260629
SUMMARY:Deadline: Van Alen Institute: Open Access - Open Call for Exhibitio
 n Proposals 2026
DESCRIPTION:Open Access: Exploring 130 Years of American Design is a reques
 t for exhibition proposals that treats the Van Alen Institute archive (tho
 usands of competition boards\, jury records\, photographs and corresponden
 ce) as living material to be questioned and reinterpreted through the lens
  of open and fair access. Van Alen invites emerging designers and creative
 s of all disciplines to engage the archive\, either responding directly to
  specific materials (competition prompts\, submitted drawings) or thematic
 ally. A wide range of media is welcomed\, including architectural models\,
  drawings\, images\, projections\, video\, photography and writing\; direc
 t engagement\, interaction and multi-disciplinary collaboration are encour
 aged. Five projects will be selected and shown together at Van Alen Instit
 ute\, 28 September to 13 November 2026. ELIGIBILITY: open to emerging crea
 tives across disciplines (architects\, artists\, designers\, filmmakers\, 
 photographers\, researchers\, writers and others)\; no formal architectura
 l training required. Applicants must be at least 18\; be legally authorize
 d to work in the United States OR capable of receiving an artist honorariu
 m (so non-US applicants able to receive an honorarium may apply\, though t
 he Brooklyn exhibition and hybrid check-ins make it US-practical)\; be ava
 ilable for hybrid check-ins July to November 2026\; and commit to deliveri
 ng exhibition-ready work on the project timeline. Collaborative proposals 
 are permitted\, though the honorarium may be shared among collaborators. S
 elected participants receive a USD 3\,000 honorarium\, archival access and
  curatorial support\, mentorship from Van Alen staff and advisors\, free m
 aterials through Materials for the Arts\, and professional documentation. 
 Supported by the National Endowment for the Arts and the New York State Co
 uncil on the Arts. Application deadline: 28 June 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Va
 n Alen Institute\nLocation: Brooklyn\, New York\, USA. Exhibition at Van A
 len Institute\, 28 September to 13 November 2026\nAward: USD 3\,000 honora
 rium\, plus archival access\, curatorial support\, mentorship\, free mater
 ials via Materials for the Arts\, professional documentation\, and inclusi
 on in the public exhibition. Five projects selected. No application fee.\n
 Duration: Hybrid project check-ins July to November 2026\; exhibition 28 S
 eptember to 13 November 2026\n\nMore: https://www.vanalen.org/project/open
 -access/
URL:https://www.vanalen.org/project/open-access/
LOCATION:Brooklyn\, New York\, USA. Exhibition at Van Alen Institute\, 28 S
 eptember to 13 November 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:exploratorium-artist-in-residence-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260628T091816Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260629
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260630
SUMMARY:Deadline: Exploratorium: Artist-in-Residence Program (AIR) 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Exploratorium's Artist-in-Residence Program (AIR)\, running
  since 1974\, works with individuals and artist groups who are drawn to co
 llaboration\, interested in interdisciplinary dialogue\, and open to devel
 oping new working methods. Projects have taken many forms: multimedia perf
 ormances\, theatrical productions\, animated filmmaking\, immersive instal
 lations\, walking tours\, and online projects. The program lets artists em
 bed within the culture of the institution (a renowned San Francisco scienc
 e museum)\, with access to its staff and a diverse public for cross-pollin
 ation. Residencies typically unfold over two years and include both an exp
 loratory phase and a project-development phase. The program is designed fo
 r artists who begin with curiosity and experimentation rather than a fully
  formed idea\, working co-creatively with the Exploratorium\; applicants s
 hould be inherently curious and deeply invested in inquiry as part of thei
 r practice. SUPPORT: a USD 15\,000 annual stipend\, travel support\, proje
 ct management and financial support for residency projects\, and access to
  Exploratorium facilities and staff expertise. Apply via the Exploratorium
  SlideRoom portal by 29 June 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Exploratorium\nLocatio
 n: San Francisco\, California\, USA (embedded within the museum)\nAward: U
 SD 15\,000 annual stipend\, plus travel support\, project management and f
 inancial support for residency projects\, and access to Exploratorium faci
 lities and staff expertise. No application fee.\nDuration: Typically two y
 ears (exploratory and project-development phases)\n\nMore: https://explora
 torium.slideroom.com/#/login/program/88782
URL:https://exploratorium.slideroom.com/#/login/program/88782
LOCATION:San Francisco\, California\, USA (embedded within the museum)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
